# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ss-agamemnon-1865
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Greek mythology, **Agamemnon** (/æɡəˈmɛmnɒn/ ⓘ; Ancient Greek: Ἀγαμέμνων *Agamémnōn*) was a king of Mycenae who commanded the Achaeans during the Trojan War.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] He was the son (or grandson) of King Atreus and Queen Aerope, the brother of Menelaus, the husband of Clytemnestra, and the father of Iphigenia, Iphianassa, Electra, Laodike, Orestes and Chrysothemis.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Legends make him the king of Mycenae or Argos, thought to be different names for the same area.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon was killed upon his return from Troy by Clytemnestra, or in an older version of the story, by Clytemnestra's lover Aegisthus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Different etymologies have been proposed for the name *Agamemnon* (Ἀγαμέμνων).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] According to one view, the name means 'very steadfast', 'unbowed' or 'resolute'.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] This is based on the interpretation of the name as a compound word comprising the elements ἄγαν 'very much' and μένω 'to stay, wait; stand fast'.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] According to another view, the name developed from the unattested form *Ἀγαμέδμων (**Agamédmōn*), a compound word composed of the elements ἄγαν 'very much' and μέδομαι 'to think on, provide for', with the overall meaning of 'very mindful'.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Yet another proposal derives the second part of the compound word from μέμονα 'to be inclined, to wish eagerly, to strive' for the overall meaning of 'very eagerly wishing'.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Linguist Václav Blažek proposes a relationship with Vedic Sanskrit *Agni* on etymological and functional bases.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon was a descendant of Pelops, son of Tantalus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] According to the common story (as told in the *Iliad* and *Odyssey* of Homer), Agamemnon and his younger brother Menelaus were the sons of Atreus, king of Mycenae, and Aerope, daughter of the Cretan king Catreus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] However, according to another tradition, Agamemnon and Menelaus were the sons of Atreus' son Pleisthenes, with their mother being Aerope, Cleolla, or Eriphyle.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In this tradition, Pleisthenes dies young, with Agamemnon and Menelaus being raised by Atreus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon had a sister Anaxibia (or Astyoche) who married Strophius, the son of Crisus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon's father, Atreus, murdered the sons of his twin brother Thyestes and fed them to Thyestes after discovering Thyestes' adultery with his wife Aerope.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Thyestes fathered Aegisthus with his own daughter, Pelopia, and this son vowed gruesome revenge on Atreus' children.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Aegisthus murdered Atreus, restored Thyestes to the throne, and took possession of the throne of Mycenae and jointly ruled with his father.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] During this period, Agamemnon and his brother Menelaus took refuge with Tyndareus, King of Sparta.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Sparta, Agamemnon and Menelaus respectively married Tyndareus' daughters Clytemnestra and Helen.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In some stories (such as *Iphigenia at Aulis* by Euripides) Clytemnestra was already married to Tantalus, and Agamemnon murders him and the couple's infant son before marrying Clytemnestra.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Menelaus succeeded Tyndareus in Sparta, while Agamemnon, with his brother's assistance, drove out Aegisthus and Thyestes to recover his father's kingdom.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] He extended his dominion by conquest and became the most powerful prince in Greece.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] The number of children Agamemnon and Clytemnestra had varies according to source.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In the *Iliad*, Agamemnon states that he has three daughters: Chrysothemis, Laodike, and Iphianassa.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Aeschylus' *Oresteia*, he has one son, Orestes, and two daughters, Iphigenia and Electra; Sophocles' *Electra* adds a daughter named Chrysothemis.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon's family history had been tarnished by murder, incest, and treachery, consequences of the heinous crime perpetrated by his ancestor, Tantalus, and then of a curse placed upon Pelops, son of Tantalus, by Myrtilus, whom he had murdered.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Aeschylus' *Oresteia*, misfortune hounded successive generations of the House of Atreus, until atoned by Orestes in a court of justice held jointly by humans and gods.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon gathers the reluctant Greek forces to sail for Troy.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In order to recruit Odysseus, who is feigning madness so as to not have to go to war, Agamemnon sends Palamedes, who threatens to kill Odysseus' infant son, Telemachus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Odysseus is forced to stop acting mad in order to save his son and joins the assembled Greek forces.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Preparing to depart from Aulis, a port in Boeotia, Agamemnon's army incurs the wrath of the goddess Artemis, although the myths give various reasons for this.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Aeschylus' play *Agamemnon*, Artemis is angry for she predicts that so many young men will die at Troy, whereas in Sophocles' *Electra*, Agamemnon has slain an animal sacred to Artemis, and subsequently boasts that he is her equal in hunting.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Misfortunes, including a plague and a lack of wind, prevent the army from sailing.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Finally, the prophet Calchas announces that the wrath of the goddess can only be propitiated by the sacrifice of Agamemnon's daughter Iphigenia.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Classical dramatizations differ on how willing either father or daughter are to this fate; some include such trickery as claiming she was to be married to Achilles, but Agamemnon does eventually sacrifice Iphigenia.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Her death appeases Artemis and the Greek army set out for Troy.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Several alternatives to the human sacrifice have been presented in Greek mythology.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Other sources, such as *Iphigenia at Aulis*, say that Agamemnon is prepared to kill his daughter but that Artemis accepts a deer in her place and whisks her away to Tauris in the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] However, this version is widely considered to be the work of an interpolator, and not Euripides himself.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Hesiod says she became the goddess Hecate.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] During the war, but before the events of the *Iliad*, Odysseus contrives a plan to get revenge on Palamedes for threatening his son's life.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] By forging a letter from Priam, king of the Trojans, and caching some gold in Palamedes' tent, Odysseus has Palamedes accused of treason and Agamemnon orders him to be stoned to death.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] The *Iliad* tells the story of the quarrel between Agamemnon and Achilles in the final year of the war.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Book One, following one of the Achaean army's raids, Chryseis, daughter of Chryses, one of Apollo's priests, is taken as a war prize by Agamemnon.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Chryses pleads with Agamemnon to free his daughter but meets with little success.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Chryses then prays to Apollo for the safe return of his daughter.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Apollo responds by unleashing a plague over the Achaean army.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] The prophet Calchas tells that the plague may be dispelled by returning Chryseis to her father.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] After bitterly berating Calchas for his painful prophecies, which first forced him to sacrifice his daughter and now to return his concubine, Agamemnon reluctantly agrees.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] However, Agamemnon demands a new prize from the army as compensation and seizes Achilles' prize, the beautiful captive Briseis.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] This creates deadly resentment between Achilles and Agamemnon, causing Achilles to withdraw from battle and refuse to fight.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon is then visited in a dream by Zeus who tells him to rally his forces and attack the Trojans (in Book Two).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] After several days of fighting, including duels between Menelaus and Paris, and between Ajax and Hector, the Achaeans are pushed back to the fortifications around their ships.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Book Nine, Agamemnon, having realized Achilles's importance in winning the war, sends ambassadors begging for Achilles to return, offering him riches and the hand of his daughter in marriage.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Achilles refuses, only being spurred back into action when his companion Patroclus is killed in battle by Hector, eldest son of King Priam and Queen Hecuba.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Book Nineteen, Agamemnon, reconciled with Achilles, gives him the offered rewards for returning to the war.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Achilles sets out to turn back the Trojans and to duel with Hector.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] After Hector's death, Agamemnon assists Achilles in performing Patroclus' funeral in Book Twenty-three.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon volunteers for the javelin throwing contest, one of the games being held in Patroclus' honor, but his skill with the javelin is so well known that Achilles awards him the prize without contest.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Although not the equal of Achilles in bravery, Agamemnon was a representative of "kingly authority".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] As commander-in-chief, he summoned the princes to the council and led the army in battle.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] His chief fault was his overwhelming haughtiness; an over-exalted opinion of his position that led him to insult Chryses and Achilles, thereby bringing great disaster upon the Greeks.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon was the commander-in-chief of the Greeks during the Trojan War.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] During the fighting, Agamemnon killed Antiphus and fifteen other Trojan soldiers, according to one source.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In the *Iliad* itself, he is shown to slaughter hundreds more in Book Eleven during his *aristeia*, loosely translated to "day of glory", which is the most similar to Achilles' *aristeia* in Book Twenty-one.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] According to Sophocles' *Ajax,* after Achilles had fallen in battle, Agamemnon and Menelaus award Achilles' armor to Odysseus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] This angers Ajax, who feels he is now the strongest among the Achaean warriors and so deserves the armor.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Ajax considers killing them, but is driven to madness by Athena and instead slaughters the herdsmen and cattle that had not yet been divided as spoils of war.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] He then commits suicide in shame for his actions.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] As Ajax dies, he curses the sons of Atreus (Agamemnon and Menelaus), along with the entire Achaean army.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon and Menelaus consider leaving Ajax's body to rot, denying him a proper burial, but are convinced otherwise by Odysseus and Ajax's half-brother Teucer.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] After the capture of Troy, Cassandra, the doomed prophetess and daughter of Priam, fell to Agamemnon's lot in the distribution of the prizes of war.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] After a stormy voyage, Agamemnon and Cassandra land in Argolis, or, in another version, are blown off course and land in Aegisthus's country.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Clytemnestra, Agamemnon's wife, has taken Aegisthus, son of Thyestes, as a lover.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] When Agamemnon comes home he is slain by Aegisthus (in the oldest versions of the story) or by Clytemnestra.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] According to the accounts given by Pindar and the tragedians, Agamemnon is slain in a bath by his wife alone, after being ensnared by a blanket or a net thrown over him to prevent resistance.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Homer's version of the story in the *Odyssey*, Aegisthus ambushes and kills Agamemnon in a feasting hall under the pretense of holding a feast in honor of Agamemnon's return home from Troy.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Her motivations are her wrath at the sacrifice of Iphigenia (as in the *Oresteia* and *Iphigenia at Aulis*) and her jealousy of Cassandra and other war prizes taken by Agamemnon (as in the *Odyssey* and works by Ovid*)*.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Aegisthus and Clytemnestra then rule Agamemnon's kingdom for a time, Aegisthus claiming his right of revenge for Atreus's crimes against Thyestes (Thyestes then crying out "thus perish all the race of Pleisthenes!", thus explaining Aegisthus' action as justified by his father's curse).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon's family history is rife with misfortune, born from several curses contributing to the miasma around the family.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] The curse begins with Agamemnon's great-grandfather Tantalus, who is in Zeus's favor until he tries to feed his son Pelops to the gods in order to test their omniscience, as well as stealing some ambrosia and nectar.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Tantalus is then banished to the underworld, where he stands in a pool of water that evaporates every time he reaches down to drink, and above him is a fruit tree whose branches are blown just out of reach by the wind whenever he reaches for the fruit.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] This begins the cursed house of Atreus, and his descendants would face similar or worse fates.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Later, using his relationship with Poseidon, Pelops convinces the god to grant him a chariot so he may beat Oenomaus, king of Pisa, in a race, and win the hand of his daughter Hippodamia.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Myrtilus, who in some accounts helps Pelops win his chariot race, attempts to lie with Pelops's new bride Hippodamia.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In anger, Pelops throws Myrtilus off a cliff, but not before Myrtilus curses Pelops and his entire line.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Pelops and Hippodamia have many children, including Atreus and Thyestes, who are said to have murdered their half-brother Chrysippus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Pelops banishes Atreus and Thyestes to Mycanae, where Atreus becomes king.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Thyestes later conspires with Atreus's wife, Aerope, to supplant Atreus, but they are unsuccessful.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Atreus then kills Thyestes' son and cooks him into a meal which Thyestes eats, and afterwards Atreus taunts him with the hands and feet of his now dead son.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Thyestes, on the advice of an oracle, then has a son with his own daughter Pelopia.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Pelopia tries to expose the infant Aegisthus, but he is found by a shepherd and raised in the house of Atreus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] When Aegisthus reaches adulthood Thyestes reveals the truth of his birth, and Aegisthus then kills Atreus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Atreus and Aerope have three children, Agamemnon, Menelaus, and Anaxibia.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] The continued miasma surrounding the house of Atreus expresses itself in several events throughout their lives.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon is forced to sacrifice his own daughter, Iphigenia, to appease the gods and allow the Greek forces to sail for Troy.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] When Agamemnon refuses to return Chryseis to her father Chryses, he brings plague upon the Greek camp.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] He is also later killed by his wife, Clytemnestra, who conspires with her new lover Aegisthus in revenge for the death of Iphigenia.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Menelaus's wife, Helen of Troy, runs away with Paris, ultimately leading to the Trojan War.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] According to book 4 of the *Odyssey,* after the war his fleet is scattered by the gods to Egypt and Crete.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] When Menelaus finally returns home, his marriage with Helen is now strained and they produce no sons.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Both Agamemnon and Menelaus are cursed by Ajax for not granting him Achilles's armor as he commits suicide.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon and Clytemnestra have three remaining children, Electra, Orestes, and Chrysothemis.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] After growing to adulthood and being pressured by Electra, Orestes vows to avenge his father Agamemnon by killing his mother Clytemnestra and Aegisthus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] After successfully doing so, he wanders the Greek countryside for many years constantly plagued by the Erinyes (Furies) for his sins.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Finally, with the help of Athena and Apollo he is absolved of his crimes, dispersing the miasma, and the curse on house Atreus comes to an end.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Athenaeus tells a tale of how Agamemnon mourns the loss of his friend or lover Argynnus, when he drowns in the Cephisus river.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] He buries him, honored with a tomb and a shrine to Aphrodite Argynnis.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] This episode is also found in Clement of Alexandria, in Stephen of Byzantium *(Kopai* and *Argunnos)*, and in Propertius, III with minor variations.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] The fortunes of Agamemnon have formed the subject of numerous tragedies, ancient and modern, the most famous being the *Oresteia* of Aeschylus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In the legends of the Peloponnesus, Agamemnon was regarded as the highest type of a powerful monarch, and in Sparta he was worshipped under the title of *Zeus Agamemnon*.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] His tomb was pointed out among the ruins of Mycenae and at Amyclae.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In works of art, there is considerable resemblance between the representations of Zeus, king of the gods, and Agamemnon, king of men.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] He is generally depicted with a sceptre and diadem, conventional attributes of kings.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] She is also one of two horses driven by Menelaus at the funeral games of Patroclus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Homer's *Odyssey* Agamemnon makes an appearance in the kingdom of Hades after his death.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] There, the former king meets Odysseus and explains just how he was murdered before he offers Odysseus a warning about the dangers of trusting a woman.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] Agamemnon is a character in William Shakespeare's play *Troilus and Cressida*, set during the Trojan War.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/agamemnon] In Frank Herbert's *Dune*, the House of Atreides trace themselves back to the House of Atreus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] Alfred Holt was one of six brothers, born to George Holt and his wife, Emma.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] In 1866, he and his brother, Philip Holt founded the Alfred Holt and Company and the Ocean Steam Ship Company, which owned and operated the majority of the company's vessels.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] Alfred Holt & Co later became Blue Funnel Line.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] One of his other brothers, George Holt, was also a noted Liverpool merchant and ship owner.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] His youngest brother, Robert Durning Holt, was Mayor of Liverpool.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] Holt served an apprenticeship under the chief engineer of the Liverpool & Manchester Railway, learning the basics of both mechanical and civil engineering.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] On finishing his apprenticeship, he established himself as an engineering consultant, and soon became involved in ship management.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] The efficiencies of compound steam engines, which were widely used in railway locomotives, were not available to steamships as the Board of trade limited the steam pressures of marine boilers to about 20 psi (140 kPa).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] Not only did Holt understand the well-known benefits of higher steam pressures running compound engines, but he also had the negotiating skills to gain the approval of the Board of Trade to put this into effect.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] The result was *Cleator*, the testbed for these ideas, running at 60 psi (410 kPa).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] Holt then set about designing a steamship for the China trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] This was a route worked almost entirely by sail.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] The Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company had a steamship route to China from Britain that went along the Mediterranean, with an overland section to the north end of the Red Sea and then to China by sea.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] A few auxiliary steamships sailed to China round the Cape of Good Hope, using their steam engines in light winds.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] The more prominent cargo vessels on this route were the clippers engaged in the tea trade, but many ordinary merchant sailing vessels also sailed to China.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] The passage from London to China is about 14,000 nautical miles.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] The problem for a steamer was to have space for enough coal for this distance, but still carry a commercial amount of cargo.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] Holt achieved a big increase in efficiency that made this possible.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] He married his first wife, Catherine Long in 1865.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] They had a daughter, Jane (1867–1922), who married the marine biologist William Abbott Herdman; a son, George, who became one of the managers of the Blue Funnel Line; and another son, who died in his teens.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] After Catherine's death in 1869, Alfred Holt married her cousin, Frances Long (in 1871), with whom he had two more sons.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/alfred-holt] The youngest son, also named Alfred (1877–1931), became a Reader in Chemistry at the University of Liverpool.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] A **barque** or **bark** is a type of sailing vessel with three or more masts of which the fore mast, mainmast, and any additional masts are rigged square, and only the aftmost mast (mizzen in three-masted barques) is rigged fore and aft.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Sometimes, the mizzen is only partly fore-and-aft rigged, bearing a square-rigged sail above.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The word "barque" entered English via the French term, which in turn came from the Latin *barca* by way of Occitan, Catalan, Spanish, or Italian.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The Latin *barca* may stem from Celtic *barc* (per Thurneysen) or Greek *baris* (per Diez), a term for an Egyptian boat.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The *Oxford English Dictionary*, however, considers the latter improbable.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The word *barc* appears to have come from Celtic languages.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The form adopted by English, perhaps from Irish, was "bark", while that adopted by Latin as *barca* very early, which gave rise to the French *barge* and *barque*.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] In Latin, Spanish, and Italian, the term *barca* refers to a small boat, not a full-sized ship.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] French influence in England led to the use in English of both words, although their meanings now are not the same.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Well before the 19th century, a barge had become interpreted as a small vessel of coastal or inland waters, or a fast rowing boat carried by warships and normally reserved for the commanding officer.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Somewhat later, a bark became a sailing vessel of a distinctive rig as detailed below.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] In Britain, by the mid-19th century, the spelling had taken on the French form of *barque*.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Although Francis Bacon used the spelling with a "q" as early as 1592, Shakespeare still used the spelling "barke" in Sonnet 116 in 1609.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Throughout the period of sail, the word was used also as a shortening of the barca-longa of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The usual modern spelling convention is that, to distinguish between homophones, when spelled as barque it refers to a ship, and when spelled as bark it refers to either a sound or to a tree hide.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] "Barcarole" in music shares the same etymology, being originally a folk song sung by Venetian gondoliers and derived from *barca*—"boat" in Italian, or in Late Latin.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] In the 18th century, the Royal Navy used the term bark for a nondescript vessel that did not fit any of its usual categories.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Thus, when the British admiralty purchased a collier for use by James Cook in his journey of exploration, she was registered as HM Bark *Endeavour* to distinguish her from another *Endeavour*, a sloop already in service at the time.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] *Endeavour* happened to be a full-rigged ship with a plain bluff bow and a full stern with windows.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] William Falconer's *Dictionary of the Marine* defined "bark", as "a general name given to small ships: it is however peculiarly appropriated by seamen to those which carry three masts without a mizzen topsail.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] A 16th-century paper document in the Cheshire and Chester Archives and Local Studies Service notes the names of Robert Ratclyfe, owner of the bark *Sunday* and 10 mariners appointed to serve under the Earl of Sussex, Lord Deputy of Ireland.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] By the end of the 18th century, the term barque (sometimes, particularly in the US, spelled bark) came to refer to any vessel with a particular type of sail plan.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] This comprises three (or more) masts, fore-and-aft sails on the aftermost mast and square sails on all other masts.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Barques were the workhorse of the golden age of sail in the mid-19th century as they attained passages that nearly matched full-rigged ships, but could operate with smaller crews.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The advantage of these rigs was that they needed smaller (therefore cheaper) crews than a comparable full-rigged ship or brig-rigged vessel, as fewer of the labour-intensive square sails were used, and the rig itself is cheaper.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Conversely, the ship rig tended to be retained for training vessels where the larger the crew, the more seamen were trained.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Another advantage is that, downwind, a barque can outperform a schooner or barkentine, and is both easier to handle and better at going to windward than a full-rigged ship.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] While a full-rigged ship is the best runner available, and while fore-and-aft rigged vessels are the best at going to windward, the barque and the barquentine, are compromises, which combine, in different proportions, the best elements of these two.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Whether square-rig, barque, barquentine or schooner is optimal depends on the degree to which the sailing-route and season can be chosen to achieve following-wind.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Square-riggers predominated for intercontinental sailing on routes chosen for following-winds.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Most ocean-going windjammers were four-masted barques, due to the above-described considerations and compromises.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Usually the main mast was the tallest; that of *Moshulu* extends to 58 m off the deck.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The four-masted barque can be handled with a surprisingly small crew—at minimum, 10—and while the usual crew was around 30, almost half of them could be apprentices.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Today many sailing-school ships are barques.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] A well-preserved example of a commercial barque is the *Pommern*, the only windjammer in original condition.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Its home is in Mariehamn outside the Åland maritime museum.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The wooden barque *Sigyn*, built in Gothenburg 1887, is now a museum ship in Turku.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Morgan*, launched 1841, taken out of service 1921, is now a museum ship at Mystic Seaport in Connecticut.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Morgan* has recently been refit and is (as of summer, 2014) sailing the New England coast.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The United States Coast Guard still has an operational barque, built in Germany in 1936 and captured as a war prize, the USCGC *Eagle*, which the United States Coast Guard Academy in New London uses as a training vessel.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The Sydney Heritage Fleet restored an iron-hulled three-masted barque, the *James Craig*, originally constructed as *Clan Macleod* in 1874 and sailing at sea fortnightly.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The oldest active sailing vessel in the world, the *Star of India*, was built in 1863 as a full-rigged ship, then converted into a barque in 1901.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] This type of ship inspired the French composer Maurice Ravel to write his famous piece, *Une Barque sur l'ocean*, originally composed for piano, in 1905, then orchestrated in 1906.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] In Ancient Egypt, barques, referred to using the French word as Egyptian hieroglyphs were first translated by the Frenchman Jean-François Champollion, were a type of boat used from Egypt's earliest recorded times and are depicted in many drawings, paintings, and reliefs that document the culture.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Transportation to the afterlife was believed to be accomplished by way of barques, as well, and the image is used in many of the religious murals and carvings in temples and tombs.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The most important Egyptian barque carried the dead pharaoh to become a deity.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Great care was taken to provide a beautiful barque to the pharaoh for this journey, and models of the boats were placed in their tombs.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Many models of these boats, that range from tiny to huge in size, have been found.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Wealthy and royal members of the culture also provided barques for their final journey.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The type of vessel depicted in Egyptian images remains quite similar throughout the thousands of years the culture persisted.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Temples included barque shrines, sometimes more than one in a temple, in which the sacred barques rested when a procession was not in progress.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] In these stations, the boats would be watched over and cared for by the priests.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] Peter, or the Barque of Peter, is a reference to the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The term refers to Peter, the first Pope, who was a fisherman before becoming an apostle of Jesus.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/barque] The Pope is often said to be steering the Barque of St.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Alfred Holt founded the business on 16 January 1866.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The main operating subsidiary was the Ocean Steam Ship Company, which owned and operated the majority of the company's vessels.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] A Dutch subsidiary, the **Nederlandsche Stoomvaart Maatschappij Oceaan**, was founded in 1891, as was the **East India Ocean Steam Ship Company**, operated from Singapore.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] This latter was sold in 1899 to Norddeutscher Lloyd.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The company acquired the competing **China Mutual Steam Navigation Company** in 1902, keeping it as a subsidiary company but operating it as part of Blue Funnel Line.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The company's ships connected the major ports of Shanghai and Hong Kong to Liverpool.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The ship's crews were Chinese as well as European.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] As a consequence, some Chinese seamen settled in Liverpool from the 1860s to found the oldest Chinese community in Europe.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Ships of the Blue Funnel fleet all had names from classical Greek legend or history.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The majority were cargo ships, but most of the Ocean SS Co cargo ships also had capacity for a few passengers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The line also had a small number of purely passenger vessels.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] In the 1920s, Blue Funnel became the first British shipping company to employ a woman marine engineer.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] These were two of the first new ships built for Blue Funnel to replace its Second World War losses.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The company expanded in 1937 through acquisition of the Glen Line in 1935, that provided cargo and passenger service to the Far East from eastern English ports such as London.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Wurtzburg, brought Herbert Gladstone McDavid to London from the company's Liverpool office as director of the new acquisition and profits increased.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Eight new Glenearn class ships were ordered, four from UK shipyards and four from abroad but not all were delivered when the Second World War started.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The first Outward Bound school was opened in Aberdyfi, Wales in 1941 with the support of the Blue Funnel Line.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Outward Bound's founding mission was to improve the survival chances of young seamen after their ships were torpedoed in the mid-Atlantic.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Captain JF "Freddy" Fuller of the Blue Funnel Line took over the leadership of the Aberdyfi school in 1942 and served the Outward Bound movement as senior warden until 1971.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Fuller was seconded following wartime experience during the Battle of the Atlantic of surviving two successive U-boat attacks and commanding an open lifeboat in the Atlantic Ocean for 35 days without losing a single member of the crew.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Blue Funnel lost 16 ships in the First World War and 30 in the Second.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] After each war it restored its fleet with new ships.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] After the Second War it regained tonnage rapidly by buying six Victory ships from the United States Maritime Commission in 1946 and eight *"Sam-"* ships from the Ministry of War Transport in 1947.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Six of the eight new ships ordered by Glen Line in 1938 were reacquired, resulting in a fleet of 15 ships by September 1948.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The twice-monthly fast service and a slower secondary service to the Far East resumed.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Two Blue Funnel ships, *Agapenor* and *Melampus* were trapped by the Six-Day War of 1967 and became part of the Yellow Fleet in the Great Bitter Lake, remaining there until 1975.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] From 1947 to 1970, as Britain's empire began to shrink, so did its trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Simultaneously, companies from other parts of the world began to operate more competitively.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Cabotage regulations prevented British flag companies from trading on routes that were previously their monopolies.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Several factors resulted in a decreased number in the Blue Funnel's fleet.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] Among the more notable of officers to work at Blue Funnel line was Richard Woodman who began his seagoing career as an apprentice with the line in 1960.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The company finally came to an end in 1988 when Ocean Group withdrew from the Barber Blue Sea Service, its last shipping line.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The Merseyside Maritime Museum Archive and Library holds the company archive.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/blue-funnel-line] The company's seafarers later went to fill various roles in the British maritime shore based establishment, including Malcolm Maclachlan, a lecturer in Glasgow and a popular author of books on maritime business.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The **Board of Trade** is a British government body concerned with commerce and industry, currently within the Department for Business and Trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The board has gone through several evolutions, beginning with extensive involvement in colonial matters in the 17th century, to powerful regulatory functions in the Victorian Era and early 20th century.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] It was virtually dormant in the last third of the 20th century.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In 2017, it was revitalised as an advisory board headed by the International Trade Secretary who has nominally held the title of President of the Board of Trade, and who at present is the only privy counsellor of the board, the other members of the present board filling roles as advisors.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The board was first established as a temporary committee of England's Privy Council to advise on colonial (plantation) questions in the early 17th century, when these settlements were initially forming.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Between 1696 and 1782 the Board of Trade, in partnership with the various secretaries of state over that time, held responsibility for colonial affairs, particularly in British America.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The newly created office of Home Secretary then held colonial responsibility until 1801, when the Secretary of State for War and the Colonies was established.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Following the loss of the American War of Independence, both the board and the short-lived secretaryship were dismissed by the king on 2 May 1782 and the board was abolished later by the Civil List and Secret Service Money Act 1782 (22 Geo.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Initially mandated by an Order in Council on 5 March 1784, the committee was reconstructed and strengthened by a second order, on 23 August 1786, under which it operated for the rest of its existence.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The committee has been known as the Board of Trade since 1786, but this name was only officially adopted by section 65 of the Harbours and Passing Tolls, &c.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The new board's first functions were consultative like earlier iterations, and its concern with plantations, in matters such as the approval of colonial laws, more successfully accomplished.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] As the Industrial Revolution expanded, the board's work became increasingly executive and domestic.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] From the 1840s, a succession of acts of Parliament gave it regulatory duties, notably concerning railways, merchant shipping and joint-stock companies.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] This department was merged with the Ministry of Technology in 1970, to form the Department of Trade and Industry.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The Secretary of State for Trade and Industry (from 2009 Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills) was also President of the Board of Trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The full board has met only once since the mid-20th century, during commemorations of the bicentenary of the board in 1986.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In 2016, the role of President of the Board of Trade was transferred to the Secretary of State for International Trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The board was reconstituted in October 2017.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The board's formal title remains "The Lords of the Committee of the Privy Council appointed for the consideration of all matters relating to Trade and Foreign Plantations".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In 1634, Charles I appointed a new commission for regulating plantations.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] It was headed by the Archbishop of Canterbury with its primary goals to increase royal authority and the influence of the Church of England in the colonies, particularly with the great influx of Puritans to the New World.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Soon after, the English Civil Wars erupted and initiated a long period of political instability in England and the resultant loss of productivity for these committees.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The war spread to varying degrees to the English colonies, depending on the internal demographics and political and religious division of each.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Between 1643 and 1648 the Long Parliament established a parliamentary Commission for Plantations to take the lead in colonial and commercial affairs.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] This period also saw the first regulation of royal tonnage and poundage and begin the modernization of customs and excise as growing sources of government revenue.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] During the Interregnum and Commonwealth three acts of the Rump Parliament in 1650 and 1651 are notable in the historical development of England's commercial and colonial programs.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] These include the first Commission of Trade to be established by an Act of Parliament on 1 August 1650.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The act's statesmanlike and comprehensive instructions, along with an October act prohibiting trade with pro-royalist colonies and the Navigation Act of October 1651, formed the first definitive expression of England's commercial policy.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] They represent the first attempt to establish a legitimate control of commercial and colonial affairs, and the instructions indicate the beginnings of a policy which had the prosperity and wealth of England exclusively at heart.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] It was the Lords of Trade who, in 1675, originated the idea of transforming all of the colonies in America into Royal Colonies for the purpose of securing English trade against the French.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Mercantile losses during the Nine Years' War, and the currency crisis that led to the Great Recoinage of 1696, led to several proposals during the early 1690s for a more effective "council of trade" to advise the government.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Reformers like Charles Davenant pushed for a council in which merchant representatives were seated, with extensive powers to regulate trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] These proposals were vigorously debated in the 3rd Parliament of William III, and became the substrate for partisan jousting, with the Court party proposing a scheme of royally-appointed commissioners, while the Country party pressed for a board appointed by Parliament.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The reaction to the 1696 Jacobite assassination plot ensured that the Court plan carried the day, but with only marginally increased powers over the old committee, scrapping more radical reform in deference to politics surrounding the royal prerogative.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In May 1696, the old committee of the Privy Council was dissolved and its powers transferred to the new board of Commissioners for Trade and Plantations.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Eight paid commissioners, over whom the senior, or "First Lord", presided, carried out the regular work of the commission.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Staff appointed to serve the board in 1696 included a secretary, a deputy secretary, some clerks, office keepers, messengers, and a necessary woman; more staff such as a solicitor and a porter were added later.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The Bishop of London was added to the *ex officio* commissioners in 1702, and the Surveyor and Auditor-General of the Plantations in 1721.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The commission carried on the work of the former Lords of Trade but also had long periods of inactivity, devolving into chaos after 1761.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The Council was dismissed by George III of Great Britain on 2 May 1782 and dissolved on 11 July 1782 by the Civil List and Secret Service Money Act 1782.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] William Pitt the Younger re-established the committee of the Privy Council in 1784, and an Order in Council of 23 August 1786 provided the formal basis that still remains in force.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] A secretariat was established which included the president, vice president and board members.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] By 1793, the board still remained in its old structure, with 20 members including the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] After 1820 the board ceased to meet regularly and the business was carried out entirely by the secretariat.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The short name of "Board of Trade" was formalised in 1861.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In the 19th century the board had an advisory function on economic activity in the UK and its empire.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] During the second half of the 19th century, it also dealt with legislation for patents, designs and trademarks, company regulation, labour and factories, merchant shipping, agriculture, transport, power etc.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Colonial matters passed to the Colonial Office and other functions were devolved to newly created departments, a process that continued for much of the 20th century.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The original commission comprised the seven (later eight) Great Officers of State, who were not required to attend meetings, and the eight paid members, who were required to attend.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The board, so constituted, had little real power, and matters related to trade and the colonies were usually within the jurisdiction of the secretaries of state and the Privy Council, with the board confining itself mainly to colonial administration.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In 1905, David Lloyd George entered the new Liberal Cabinet of Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman as President of the Board of Trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The first priority on taking office was the repeal of the Education Act 1902.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Lloyd George took the lead along with Augustine Birrell, President of the Board of Education.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Lloyd George was the dominant figure on the committee drawing up the bill in its later stages and insisted that the bill create a separate education committee for Wales.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The bill passed the House of Commons greatly amended but was completely mangled by the House of Lords.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] No compromise was possible and the bill was abandoned, allowing the 1902 act to continue in effect.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Nonconformists were bitterly upset by the failure of the Liberal Party to reform the Education Act 1902, its most important promise to them, and over time their support for the Liberal Party slowly fell away.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] According to Martin Roberts, Lloyd George headed a department of 750 experts that was responsible for supervising British industry, commerce and transportation.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Using their pool of expertise, he initiated a series of reforms that were quickly endorsed by the Liberal Parliament.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] One of the first actions was the Census of Production Act 1906 (6 Edw.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] 49), which generated a Survey of production—an up-to-date compendium of detailed statistics necessary for regulating specific industries.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The Merchant Shipping Act 1906 upgraded the minimum working conditions, and the safety protections for both British sailors, and crews of foreign ships that used British ports.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The Patents and Design Act 1907 gave financial protection to British designs to stop unfair foreign copies.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In the long term, his most important innovation was the Port of London Act 1908 creating the Port of London Authority.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] It merged numerous inefficient and overlapping private companies and gave unified supervision to Britain's most important port.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] That enabled London to compete more effectively with Hamburg and Rotterdam.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Lloyd George also turned his attention to strikes and industrial disputes in shipyards.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] He was instrumental in settling the serious threat of a national railway strike in 1907.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] While almost all the rail companies refused to recognise the unions, he persuaded them to recognise elected representatives of the workers who sat with the company representatives on conciliation boards—one for each company.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] If those boards failed to agree then an arbitrator would be called upon.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Asquith succeeded the terminally ill prime minister on 8 April 1908 and, four days later, Winston Churchill was appointed President of the Board of Trade, succeeding Lloyd George who became Chancellor of the Exchequer.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] He continued the reform impulse Lloyd George had launched.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] One of Churchill's first tasks was to arbitrate in an industrial dispute among ship-workers and employers on the River Tyne.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] He afterwards established a Standing Court of Arbitration to deal with future industrial disputes, establishing a reputation as a conciliator.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In Cabinet, he worked with Lloyd George to champion social reform.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] He promoted what he called a "network of State intervention and regulation" akin to that in Germany.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Churchill's main achievements came in 1909.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] It set up over 200 labour exchanges with William Beveridge in charge.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The unemployed would come in and be assisted in finding employment.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] He also promoted the idea of an unemployment insurance scheme, which would be part-funded by the state.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Secondly he introduced the Trade Boards Bill, creating trade boards which investigated the sweated trades and enabled the prosecution of exploitative employers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Passing with a large majority, it established the principle of a minimum wage and the right of workers to have meal breaks.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Churchill introduced the Mines Eight Hours Bill, which legally prohibited miners from working more than an eight-hour day.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] Sydney Buxton served as president between 1910 and 1914.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] His main role was passage of numerous specific trade and commerce laws.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] From 1973, international trade policy of the United Kingdom was a competence of the European Economic Community, and later of the European Union.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The board was reconstituted in October 2017, after the UK had voted to leave the European Union in June 2016.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] In its most recent iteration in 2017, only privy counsellors can be actual members of the board, while others are appointed as advisers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] There is only one standing member in the Board, who is its President.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/board-of-trade] The Board is held accountable to Parliament through ministers attached to the Board, who are not necessarily members.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The **Cape of Good Hope** (Afrikaans: *Kaap de Goede Hoop* [ˌkaːb də ˌɣudə ˈɦoːp] ⓘ; Portuguese: *Cabo da Boa Esperança* [ˈkaβu ðɐ ˈβoɐ (ɨ)ʃpɨˈɾɐ̃sɐ]) is a rocky headland on the Atlantic coast of the Cape Peninsula in South Africa.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] A common misconception is that the Cape of Good Hope is the southern tip of Africa, based on the misbelief that the Cape was the dividing point between the Atlantic and Indian oceans.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] In fact, the southernmost point of Africa is Cape Agulhas about 150 kilometres (90 mi) to the east-southeast.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The currents of the two oceans meet at the point where the warm-water Agulhas current meets the cold-water Benguela current and turns back on itself.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] That oceanic meeting point fluctuates between Cape Agulhas and Cape Point (about 1.2 kilometres (0.75 mi) east of the Cape of Good Hope).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] is the southernmost part of South Africa.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] When following the western side of the African coastline from the equator, however, the Cape of Good Hope marks the point where a ship begins to travel more eastward than southward.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Thus, the first modern rounding of the cape in 1487 by Portuguese explorer Bartolomeu Dias was a milestone in the attempts by the Portuguese to establish direct trade relations with the Far East (although Herodotus mentioned a claim that the Phoenicians had done so far earlier).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Dias called the cape *Cabo das Tormentas* ('Cape of Storms'; Dutch: *Stormkaap*), which was the original name of the cape.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] As one of the great capes of the South Atlantic Ocean, it has long been of special significance to sailors, many of whom refer to it simply as "**the Cape**".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] It is a waypoint on the Cape Route and the clipper route followed by clipper ships to the Far East and Australia, and still followed by several offshore yacht races.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Around 600 BC, Necho II reputedly commissioned an expedition of Phoenicians, who are said to have sailed for three years from the Red Sea around Africa back to the mouth of the Nile; and this would thereby be the first completion of the Cape Route.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] 130 BC) was a Greek navigator for Ptolemy VIII, king of the Hellenistic Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] In or about 116 BCE, while returning from a voyage to India, Eudoxus found the wreck of a ship that appeared to have originated in Gades (later Cádiz), in what was then Roman Hispania Baetica.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] At the time, the only way such a vessel could have reached the Indian Ocean was by rounding the Cape.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] When Eudoxus was returning from his second voyage to India, the wind forced him south of the Gulf of Aden and down the coast of Africa for some distance.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Somewhere along the coast of East Africa, he found the remains of the ship.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Due to its appearance and the story told by the natives, Eudoxus concluded that the ship was from Gades and had sailed anti-clockwise around Africa, passing the Cape and entering the Indian Ocean.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] This inspired him to repeat the voyage and attempt a circumnavigation of the continent.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Organising the expedition on his own account, he set sail from Gades and began to work down the African coast.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The difficulties were too great, however, and he was obliged to return to Europe.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] After this failure, he again set out to circumnavigate Africa.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Although some, such as Pliny, claimed that Eudoxus did achieve his goal, the most probable conclusion is that he died on the journey.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] In the 1450 Fra Mauro map, the Indian Ocean is depicted as connected to the Atlantic.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] This knowledge, together with the map depiction of the African continent, probably encouraged the Portuguese to intensify their effort to round the tip of Africa.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] In 1511, after Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca, the Portuguese recovered a chart from a Javanese maritime pilot, which, according to Albuquerque, already included the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] In the Early Modern Era, the first European to reach the cape was the Portuguese explorer Bartolomeu Dias on 12 March 1488, who named it the "Cape of Storms" (*Cabo das Tormentas*).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] It was later renamed by John II of Portugal as "Cape of Good Hope" (*Cabo da Boa Esperança*) because of the great optimism engendered by the opening of a sea route to India and the East.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Khoikhoi people lived in the cape area when the Dutch first settled there in 1652.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Khoikhoi had arrived in this area about fifteen hundred years before.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Dutch called them *Hottentots*, a term that has now come to be regarded as pejorative.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] In 1652, the Dutch East India Company's administrator Jan van Riebeeck established a resupply camp for the Dutch East India Company some 50 km north of the cape in Table Bay on April 6, and this eventually developed into Cape Town.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Supplies of fresh food were vital on the long journey around Africa and Cape Town became known as "The Tavern of the Seas".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] On 31 December 1687, a community of Huguenots (French Protestants) arrived at the Cape of Good Hope from the Netherlands.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] They had fled from France due to religious persecution and gone to the Netherlands, before making the journey to the Cape Colony.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Members of this group included Pierre Joubert, who came from La Motte-d'Aigues, as well as Jean Roy.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Dutch East India Company needed skilled farmers at the Cape of Good Hope and the Dutch government saw opportunities to settle Huguenots at the Cape.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The colony gradually grew over the 150 years that followed until it extended hundreds of kilometers to the north and the north-east.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] During the French Revolutionary Wars, the Dutch Republic was occupied by the French in 1795.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape Colony then became a French vassal and enemy of the British, who were at war with France.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] British troops invaded and occupied the Cape Colony that same year.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The British relinquished control of the territory in 1803, under the peace of Amiens, but reoccupied the colony on 19 January 1806 following the Battle of Blaauwberg.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Dutch formally ceded the territory to the British in the Anglo-Dutch Treaty of 1814.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] It would remain a separate British colony until its incorporation into the Union of South Africa in 1910.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Portuguese government erected two navigational beacons, **Dias Cross** and **da Gama Cross**, to commemorate Bartolomeu Dias and Vasco da Gama, who were the first modern European explorers to reach the cape.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] When lined up, these crosses point to Whittle Rock, a large, permanently submerged shipping hazard in False Bay.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Two other beacons in Simon's Town provide the intersection.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope saw an increase of ship activity after the 2021 Suez canal obstruction, and the Red Sea Crisis with ships needing a different route from the Indian Ocean.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope route took a toll on the sea freight industry—stretching the transit time, reducing carriers availability, and skyrocketing shipment cost and container hire.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Carriers' attempts to resort to the Red Sea route came at the expense of vessels and seafarers' safety as the Red Sea witnessed multiple sunken carriers struck by Houthi rebels.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Many large shipping companies and industries were afflicted by the situation such as IKEA, Amazon, Automotive companies, and Maersk.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope is at the southern tip of the Cape Peninsula, about 2.3 kilometers (1.4 mi) west and a little north of Cape Point on the south-east corner.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Cape Town is about 50 kilometers to the north of the Cape, in Table Bay at the north end of the peninsula.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The peninsula forms the western boundary of False Bay.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Geologically, the rocks found at the two capes, and indeed over much of the peninsula, are part of the Cape Supergroup, and are formed of the same type of sandstones as Table Mountain itself.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Both the Cape of Good Hope and Cape Point offer spectacular scenery; the whole of the southernmost portion of the Cape Peninsula is a wild, rugged, scenic and generally unspoiled national park.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The term "the Cape" has also been used in a wider sense, to indicate the area of the European colony centered on Cape Town, and the later South African province.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Since 1994, it has been broken up into three smaller provinces: the Western Cape, Eastern Cape, and Northern Cape; parts of the province were also absorbed into the North West.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] With its diverse habitat, ranging from rocky mountain tops to beaches and open sea, the Cape of Good Hope is home to at least 250 species of birds including one of the two mainland colonies of African penguins.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] "Bush birds" tend to be rather scarce because of the coarse, scrubby nature of fynbos vegetation.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] When flowering, however, proteas and ericas attract sunbirds, sugarbirds, and other species in search of nectar.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] For most of the year, there are more small birds in coastal thicket than in fynbos.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope section of Table Mountain National Park is home to several species of antelope.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Bontebok and eland are easily seen, and red hartebeest can be seen in the grazing lawns in Smitswinkel Flats.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Grey rhebok are less commonly seen and are scarce, but may be observed along the beach hills at Olifantsbos.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Most visitors are unlikely to ever see either Cape grysbok or klipspringer.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope section is home to four Cape mountain zebra.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] They might be seen by the attentive or lucky visitor, usually in Smitswinkel Flats.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] There are a wealth of small animals such as lizards, snakes, tortoises and insects.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Small mammals include rock hyrax, four-striped grass mouse, water mongoose, Cape clawless otter and fallow deer.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The area offers excellent vantage points for whale watching.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The southern right whale is the species most likely to be seen in False Bay between June and November.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Other species are the humpback whale and Bryde's whale.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Seals, dusky dolphins and orcas have also been seen.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The strategic position of the Cape of Good Hope between two major ocean currents, ensures a rich diversity of marine life.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] There is a difference between the sea life west of Cape Point and that to the east due to the markedly differing sea temperatures.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The South African Marine Living Resources Act is strictly enforced throughout the Table Mountain National Park, and especially in marine protected areas.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Disturbance or removal of any marine organisms is strictly prohibited between Schusters Bay and Hoek van Bobbejaan, but is allowed in other areas during season and with relevant permits.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Chacma baboons (*Papio ursinus*) are the mammals most intimately associated with the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Baboons inside the Cape of Good Hope section of the park are a major tourist attraction.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] There are 11 troops consisting of about 375 individuals throughout the entire Cape Peninsula.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Six of these 11 troops either live entirely within the Cape of Good Hope section of the park, or use the section as part of their range.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape Point, Kanonkop, Klein Olifantsbos, and Buffels Bay troops live entirely inside the Cape of Good Hope section of the Park.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Groot Olifantsbos and Plateau Road troops range into the park.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Chacma baboons are widely distributed across southern Africa and are classified as "least concern" in the *IUCN Red List of Threatened Species*.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] However, the South African Parks Department states in its publication *Mountains in the Sea* that the baboon population on the Cape is "critically endangered." This is due to habitat loss, genetic isolation, and conflicts with humans.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Cape baboons have been eliminated from the majority of their range across the Cape Peninsula, and the Cape of Good Hope section of Table Mountain National Park provides a sanctuary for the troops that live within its boundaries.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] It provides relative safety from nearby towns, where people have killed many baboons after the baboons raid their houses looking for food.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Baboons are also frequently injured or killed outside of the park by cars and by electrocution on power lines.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Inside the park, some management policies such as allowing barbecues and picnics in the baboon home ranges cause detriment to the troops, as they become embroiled in conflicts with guests to the park.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] At the Cape in particular, the baboon is known for eating shellfish and other marine invertebrates.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] In 1842, Charles Hamilton Smith had described a black-maned lion from the Cape under the scientific name *Felis (Leo) melanochaita*.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] No longer seen as a subspecies of its own, the Cape lion as a population is now extinct in the wilderness, though descendants could exist in captivity.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The Cape of Good Hope is an integral part of the Cape Floristic Kingdom, the smallest but richest of the world's six floral kingdoms.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] This comprises a treasure trove of 1100 species of indigenous plants, of which a number are endemic (occur naturally nowhere else on earth).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] The main type of fynbos ("fine bush") vegetation at the Cape of Good Hope is Peninsula Sandstone Fynbos, an endangered vegetation type that is endemic to the Cape Peninsula.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Coastal Hangklip Sand Fynbos grows on low-lying alkaline sands and, right by the sea, small patches of Cape Flats Dune Strandveld can be found.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Characteristic fynbos plants include proteas, ericas (heath), and restios (reeds).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Some of the most striking and well-known members belong to the Proteaceae family, of which up to 24 species occur.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] These include king protea, sugarbush, tree pincushion and golden cone bush (*Leucadendron laureolum*).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/cape-of-good-hope] Many popular horticultural plants like pelargoniums, freesias, daisies, lilies and irises also have their origins in fynbos.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] A **clipper** was a type of mid-19th-century merchant sailing vessel, designed for speed.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The term was also retrospectively applied to the Baltimore clipper, which originated in the late 18th century.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Clippers were generally narrow for their length, small by later 19th-century standards, could carry limited bulk freight, and had a large total sail area.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] "Clipper" does not refer to a specific sailplan; clippers may be schooners, brigs, brigantines, etc., as well as full-rigged ships.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Clippers were mostly constructed in British and American shipyards, although France, Brazil, the Netherlands, and other nations also produced some.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Clippers sailed all over the world, primarily on the trade routes between the United Kingdom and China, in transatlantic trade, and on the New York-to-San Francisco route around Cape Horn during the California gold rush.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Dutch clippers were built beginning in the 1850s for the tea trade and passenger service to Java.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The boom years of the clipper era began in 1843 in response to a growing demand for faster delivery of tea from China and continued with the demand for swift passage to gold fields in California and Australia beginning in 1848 and 1851, respectively.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The era ended with the opening of the Panama Railroad in 1855 and the Suez Canal in 1869.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The etymological origin of the word clipper is uncertain, but is believed to be derived from the English language verb "to clip", which at the time meant "to run or fly swiftly".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The first application of the term "clipper", in a nautical sense, is likewise uncertain.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The type known as the Baltimore clipper originated at the end of the 18th century on the eastern seaboard of the United States.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] At first, these fast sailing vessels were referred to as "Virginia-built" or "pilot-boat model", with the name "Baltimore-built" appearing during the War of 1812.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] In the final days of the slave trade (*circa* 1835–1850) – just as the type was dying out – the term, Baltimore clipper, came into frequent use.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The common retrospective application of the word "clipper" to this type of vessel has caused confusion.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The Oxford English Dictionary's earliest quote (referring to the Baltimore clipper) is from 1824.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The dictionary cites Royal Navy officer and novelist Frederick Marryat as using the term in 1830.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] British newspaper usage of the term can be found as early as 1832 and in shipping advertisements from 1835.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] A US court case of 1834 has evidence that discusses a clipper being faster than a brig.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] A clipper is a sailing vessel designed for speed, a priority that takes precedence over cargo-carrying capacity or building or operating costs.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] It is not restricted to any one rig (while many were fully rigged ships, others were barques, brigs, or schooners), nor was the term restricted to any one hull type.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Howard Chapelle lists three basic hull types for clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The first was characterised by the sharp deadrise and ends found in the Baltimore clipper.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The second was a hull with a full midsection and modest deadrise, but sharp ends – this was a development of the hull form of transatlantic packets.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The third was more experimental, with deadrise and sharpness being balanced against the need to carry a profitable quantity of cargo.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] A clipper carried a large sail area and a fast hull; by the standards of any other type of sailing ship, a clipper was greatly over-canvassed.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The last defining feature of a clipper, in the view of maritime historian David MacGregor, was a captain who had the courage, skill, and determination to get the fastest speed possible out of her.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] In assessing the hull of a clipper, different maritime historians use different criteria to measure "sharpness", "fine lines" or "fineness", a concept which is explained by comparing a rectangular cuboid with the underwater shape of a vessel's hull.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The more material one has to carve off the cuboid to achieve the hull shape, the sharper the hull.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Ideally, a maritime historian would be able to look at either the block coefficient of fineness or the prismatic coefficient of various clippers, but measured drawings or accurate half models may not exist to calculate either of these figures.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] An alternative measure of sharpness for hulls of a broadly similar shape is the coefficient of underdeck tonnage, as used by David MacGregor in comparing tea clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] This could be calculated from the measurements taken to determine the registered tonnage, so can be applied to more vessels.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] An extreme clipper has a hull of great fineness, as judged either by the prismatic coefficient, the coefficient of underdeck tonnage, or some other technical assessment of hull shape.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] This term has been misapplied in the past, without reference to hull shape.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] As commercial vessels, these are totally reliant on speed to generate a profit for their owners, as their sharpness limits their cargo-carrying capacity.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] A medium clipper has a cargo-carrying hull that has some sharpness.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] In the right conditions and with a capable captain, some of these achieved notable quick passages.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] They were also able to pay their way when the high freight rates often paid to a fast sailing ship were not available (in a fluctuating market).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The term "clipper" applied to vessels between these two categories.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] They often made passages as fast as extreme clippers, but had less difficulty in making a living when freight rates were lower.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The first ships to which the term "clipper" seems to have been applied were the Baltimore clippers, developed in the Chesapeake Bay before the American Revolution, and reached their zenith between 1795 and 1815.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] They were small, rarely exceeding 200 tons OM.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Their hulls were sharp ended and displayed much deadrise.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] They were rigged as schooners, brigs, or brigantines.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] In the War of 1812, some were lightly armed, sailing under letters of marque and reprisal, when the type – exemplified by *Chasseur*, launched at Fells Point, Baltimore in 1814 – became known for her incredible speed; the deep draft enabled the Baltimore clipper to sail close to the wind.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Clippers, running the British blockade of Baltimore, came to be recognized for speed rather than cargo space.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] A 1789 drawing of HMS *Berbice* (1780) – purchased by the Royal Navy in 1780 in the West Indies – represents the earliest draught of what became known as the Baltimore clipper.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Vessels of the Baltimore clipper type continued to be built for the slave trade, being useful for escaping enforcement of the British and American legislation prohibiting the trans-Atlantic slave trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Some of these Baltimore clippers were captured when working as slavers, condemned by the appropriate court, and sold to owners who then used them as opium clippers – moving from one illegal international trade to another.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] In Aberdeen, Scotland, shipbuilders Alexander Hall and Sons developed the "Aberdeen" clipper bow in the late 1830s; the first was *Scottish Maid* launched in 1839.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] *Scottish Maid*, 150 tons OM, was the first British clipper ship.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] "*Scottish Maid* was intended for the Aberdeen-London trade, where speed was crucial to compete with steamships.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The Hall brothers tested various hulls in a water tank and found the clipper design most effective.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The design was influenced by tonnage regulations.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Tonnage measured a ship's cargo capacity and was used to calculate tax and harbour dues.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The new 1836 regulations measured depth and breadth with length measured at half midship depth.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Extra length above this level was tax-free and became a feature of clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] *Scottish Maid* proved swift and reliable and the design was widely copied." The earliest British clipper ships were built for trade within the British Isles (*Scottish Maid* was built for the Aberdeen to London trade).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Then followed the vast clipper trade of tea, opium, spices, and other goods from the Far East to Europe, and the ships became known as "tea clippers".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] From 1839, larger American clipper ships started to be built beginning with *Akbar*, 650 tons OM, in 1839, and including the 1844-built *Houqua*, 581 tons OM.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] These larger vessels were built predominantly for use in the China tea trade and known as "tea clippers".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Then in 1845 *Rainbow*, 757 tons OM, the first extreme clipper, was launched in New York.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] These American clippers were larger vessels designed to sacrifice cargo capacity for speed.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] They had a bow lengthened above the water, a drawing out and sharpening of the forward body, and the greatest breadth further aft.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Extreme clippers were built in the period 1845 to 1855.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] In 1851, shipbuilders in Medford, Massachusetts, built what is sometimes called one of the first medium clippers, the *Antelope*, often called the *Antelope of Boston* to distinguish her from other ships of the same name.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] A contemporary ship-design journalist noted that "the design of her model was to combine large stowage capacity with good sailing qualities." *Antelope* was relatively flat-floored and had only an 8-inch deadrise at half-floor.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The medium clipper, though still very fast, could carry more cargo.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] After 1854, extreme clippers were replaced in American shipbuilding yards by medium clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The *Flying Cloud* was a clipper ship built in 1851 that established the fastest passage between New York and San Francisco within weeks of her launching, then broke her own records three years later, which stood at 89 days 8 hours until 1989.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] (The other contender for this "blue ribbon" title was the medium clipper *Andrew Jackson* – an unresolvable argument exists over timing these voyages "from pilot to pilot").
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] *Flying Cloud* was the most famous of the clippers built by Donald McKay.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] She was known for her extremely close race with the *Hornet* in 1853; for having a woman navigator, Eleanor Creesy, wife of Josiah Perkins Creesy, who skippered the *Flying Cloud* on two record-setting voyages from New York to San Francisco; and for sailing in the Australia and timber trades.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Clipper ships largely ceased being built in American shipyards in 1859 when, unlike the earlier boom years, only four clipper ships were built; a few were built in the 1860s.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] British clipper ships continued to be built after 1859.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] From 1859, a new design was developed for British clipper ships that was nothing like the American clippers; these ships continued to be called extreme clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The new design had a sleek, graceful appearance, less sheer, less freeboard, lower bulwarks, and smaller breadth.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] They were built for the China tea trade, starting with *Falcon* in 1859, and continuing until 1870.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The earlier ships were made from wood, though some were made from iron, just as some British clippers had been made from iron prior to 1859.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] In 1863, the first tea clippers of composite construction were brought out, combining the best of both worlds.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Composite clippers had the strength of an iron hull framework but with wooden planking that, with properly insulated fastenings, could use copper sheathing without the problem of galvanic corrosion.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Copper sheathing prevented fouling and teredo worm, but could not be used on iron hulls.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The iron framework of composite clippers was less bulky and lighter, so allowing more cargo in a hull of the same external shape.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] After 1869, with the opening of the Suez Canal that greatly advantaged steam vessels (see Decline below), the tea trade collapsed for clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] From the late 1860s until the early 1870s, the clipper trade increasingly focused on the Britain to Australia and New Zealand route, carrying goods and immigrants, services that had begun earlier with the Australian Gold Rush of the 1850s.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] British-built clipper ships and many American-built, British-owned ships were used.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Even in the 1880s, sailing ships were still the main carriers of cargo between Britain, and Australia and New Zealand.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] This trade eventually became unprofitable, and the ageing clipper fleet became unseaworthy.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Before the early 18th century, the East India Company paid for its tea mainly in silver.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] When the Chinese emperor chose to embargo European-manufactured commodities and demand payment for all Chinese goods in silver, the price rose, restricting trade.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The East India Company began to produce opium in India, something desired by the Chinese as much as tea was by the British.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] This had to be smuggled into China on smaller, fast-sailing ships, called "opium clippers".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Some of these were built specifically for the purpose – mostly in India and Britain, such as the 1842-built *Ariel*, 100 tons OM.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Some fruit schooners were bought for this trade, as were some Baltimore clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Among the most notable clippers were the China clippers, also called tea clippers, designed to ply the trade routes between Europe and the East Indies.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The last example of these still in reasonable condition is *Cutty Sark*, preserved in dry dock at Greenwich, United Kingdom.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Damaged by fire on 21 May 2007 while undergoing conservation, the ship was permanently elevated 3.0 m above the dry dock floor in 2010 as part of a plan for long-term preservation.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Clippers were built for seasonal trades such as tea, where an early cargo was more valuable, or for passenger routes.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] One passenger ship survives, the *City of Adelaide* designed by William Pile of Sunderland.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The fast ships were ideally suited to low-volume, high-profit goods, such as tea, opium, spices, people, and mail.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The *Challenger* returned from Shanghai with "the most valuable cargo of tea and silk ever to be laden in one bottom".
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Competition among the clippers was public and fierce, with their times recorded in the newspapers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The last China clippers had peak speeds over 16 knots (30 km/h), but their average speeds over a whole voyage were substantially less.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The joint winner of the Great Tea Race of 1866 logged about 15,800 nautical miles on a 99-day trip.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] This gives an average speed slightly over 6.6 knots (12.2 km/h).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The key to a fast passage for a tea clipper was getting across the China Sea against the monsoon winds that prevailed when the first tea crop of the season was ready.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] These difficult sailing conditions (light and/or contrary winds) dictated the design of tea clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The US clippers were designed for the strong winds encountered on their route around Cape Horn.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Donald McKay's *Sovereign of the Seas* reported the highest speed ever achieved by a sailing ship of the era, 22 knots (41 km/h), made while running her easting down to Australia in 1854.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] (John Griffiths' first clipper, the *Rainbow*, had a top speed of 14 knots.) Eleven other instances are reported of a ship's logging 18 knots (33 km/h) or over.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Ten of these were recorded by American clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Besides the breath-taking 465-nautical-mile (861 km) day's run of the *Champion of the Seas*, 13 other cases are known of a ship's sailing over 400 nautical miles (740 km) in 24 hours.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] With few exceptions, though, all the port-to-port sailing records are held by the American clippers.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The 24-hour record of the *Champion of the Seas*, set in 1854, was not broken until 1984 (by a multihull), or 2001 (by another monohull).
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The American clippers sailing from the East Coast to the California goldfields were working in a booming market.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Freight rates were high everywhere in the first years of the 1850s.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The ports of California and Australia reported that they were overstocked with goods that had been shipped earlier in the year.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] This gave an accelerating fall in freight rates that was halted, however, by the start of the Crimean War in March 1854, as many ships were now being chartered by the French and British governments.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The end of the Crimean War in April 1856 released all this capacity back on the world shipping markets – the result being a severe slump.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The next year had the Panic of 1857, with effects on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The United States was just starting to recover from this in 1861 when the American Civil War started, causing significant disruption to trade in both Union and Confederate states.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] As the economic situation deteriorated in 1853, American shipowners either did not order new vessels, or specified an ordinary clipper or a medium clipper instead of an extreme clipper.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] No extreme clipper was launched in an American shipyard after the end of 1854 and only a few medium clippers after 1860.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] By contrast, British trade recovered well at the end of the 1850s.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Tea clippers had continued to be launched during the depressed years, apparently little affected by the economic downturn.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The long-distance route to China was not realistically challenged by steamships in the early part of the 1860s.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] No true steamer (as opposed to an auxiliary steamship) had the fuel efficiency to carry sufficient cargo to make a profitable voyage.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The auxiliary steamships struggled to make any profit.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The situation changed in 1866 when the Alfred Holt-designed and owned SS *Agamemnon* made her first voyage to China.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Holt had persuaded the Board of Trade to allow higher steam pressures in British merchant vessels.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Running at 60 psi instead of the previously permitted 25 psi, and using an efficient compound engine, *Agamemnon* had the fuel efficiency to steam at 10 knots to China and back, with coaling stops at Mauritius on the outward and return legs – crucially carrying sufficient cargo to make a profit.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] In 1869, the Suez Canal opened, giving steamships a route about 3,000 nautical miles (5,600 km; 3,500 mi) shorter than that taken by sailing ships round the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Despite initial conservatism by tea merchants, by 1871, tea clippers found strong competition from steamers in the tea ports of China.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] A typical passage time back to London for a steamer was 58 days, while the fastest clippers could occasionally make the trip in less than 100 days; the average was 123 days in the 1867–68 tea season.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The freight rate for a steamer in 1871 was roughly double that paid to a sailing vessel.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Some clipper owners were severely caught out by this; several extreme clippers had been launched in 1869, including *Cutty Sark*, *Norman Court* and *Caliph*.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Of the many clipper ships built during the mid-19th century, only two are known to survive.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The only intact survivor is *Cutty Sark*, which was preserved as a museum ship in 1954 at Greenwich for public display.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The other known survivor is *City of Adelaide*; unlike *Cutty Sark*, she was reduced to a hulk over the years.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] She eventually sank at her moorings in 1991, but was raised the following year, and remained on dry land for years.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] *Carrick*) is the older of the two survivors, and was transported to Australia for conservation.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Departures of clipper ships, mostly from New York and Boston to San Francisco, were advertised by clipper-ship sailing cards.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] These cards, slightly larger than today's postcards, were produced by letterpress and wood engraving on coated card stock.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] Most clipper cards were printed in the 1850s and 1860s, and represented the first pronounced use of color in American advertising art.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] With their rarity and importance as artifacts of nautical, Western, and printing history, clipper cards are valued by both private collectors and institutions.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The Los Angeles Clippers of the National Basketball Association take their name from the type of ship.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] After the Buffalo Braves moved to San Diego, California in 1978, a contest was held to choose a new name.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The winning name highlighted the city's connection with the clippers that frequented San Diego Bay.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The team retained the name in its 1984 move to Los Angeles.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The airline Pan Am named its aircraft beginning with the word 'Clipper' and used Clipper as its callsign.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] This was intended to evoke an image of speed and glamour.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/clipper] The Europa Clipper is a NASA probe that is currently on a mission to explore Jupiter and its moons; it was launched in 2024 and is expected to reach Jupiter in 2030.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Before *Agamemnon*, steamships were not a practical commercial option for trade between Britain and the Far East.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] The amount of coal that they needed to carry left little space for cargo.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] *Agamemnon* could steam at 10 knots (19 km/h), consuming only 20 tons of coal a day.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] This was substantially less than other ships of the time – a saving of between 14 and 23 tons per day was achieved.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] This enabled her to steam to China with a coaling stop at Mauritius on the outward and return journey.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] This was the first of five Blue Funnel ships to be named after Agamemnon, the king of Mycenae during the Trojan War.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Later examples include a motor ship *Agamemnon* built in 1929, which in the Second World War was converted into an auxiliary minelayer.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] The first was a higher boiler pressure than was normally used on British merchant ships.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Alfred Holt had experimented with a boiler pressure of 60 psi in the *Cleator*, a ship he used as a floating testbed.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Holt overcame the Board of Trade's objections to boiler pressures above 25 psi in seagoing vessels.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] The second feature was her compound steam engine, designed by Alfred Holt.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] As well as being more efficient than others of the time, it was a relatively compact engine, so used less cargo space.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] The third was an iron hull that was strong in relation to its weight and cost and with modest power requirements – again developed by Alfred Holt.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Her normal journey time from Fuzhou (Foochow) to Liverpool was 58 days, whereas clippers could take anything from a record-breaking 88 days to 140 or more, and averaged 123 days in 1867–68.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Further, her cargo carrying capacity was two or three times as much as these sailing ships.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Scott built *Agamemnon* as yard number 116, launched her on 25 November 1865 and completed her on 31 March 1866.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Alfred Holt registered her at Liverpool.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Her UK official number was 54924, and by 1871 her code letters were JKGB.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] The newly built *Agamemnon* arrived in Liverpool from Greenock on 1 April 1866, the year of the clippers' Great Tea Race.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Her outward passage was the quickest recorded to date, reaching Mauritius in 40 days and Singapore in 60.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] The whole journey from Liverpool to Hong Kong took 65 days.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] This beat the fastest tea clipper outward passage of 77 days by the *Cairngorm* in 1853.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] The opening of the Suez Canal in 1869 guaranteed the success of *Agamemnon* and her sister ships by shortening the route that a steamship could take from Europe to China whilst sailing vessels still had to travel via the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] In a few years the predominance of tea clippers in the China trade had ceased.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] Associates and competitors of Alfred Holt built similar ships and the nature of long-distance maritime trade had taken a major technological change.
[src:ss-agamemnon-1865/ss-agamemnon-1865] In 1897 *Agamemnon* was transferred to Alfred Holt's Dutch subsidiary *Nederlandsche Stoomboot Maatschappij Ocean*.
